MEDIUM|internal/history/filter.go:32|ParseSince silently accepts invalid/out-of-range --since values instead of rejecting them as a usage error. strconv.ParseFloat accepts "Inf" and enormous magnitudes; the subsequent time.Duration(n * float64(per)) saturates to a positive MaxInt64 (~292y), so "--since Infd", "--since 1e30d", and "--since 200000d" all pass the d<=0 guard and exit 0 with a saturated window rather than exiting 2 with an error. Empirically confirmed on darwin/arm64. A malformed --since should be a usage error, and a requested magnitude that cannot be represented should be rejected, not silently truncated.|In filter.go ParseSince after ParseFloat, reject non-finite input with math.IsInf(n,0)||math.IsNaN(n), then range-check before converting: compute nanos := n * float64(per) and reject when nanos >= float64(math.MaxInt64) or nanos <= 0. Do not rely on time.Duration overflow saturation as validation. Add table tests for Infd, 1e30d, 200000d asserting an error.|error-handling|30|internal/history/filter.go:20-44|claude
MEDIUM|internal/history/reader.go:47|Load hard-fails on a single line longer than the 1MiB scanner cap, bricking the entire history read. When sc.Scan() hits an oversized line it stops and sc.Err() returns bufio.ErrTooLong, so Load returns (nil, error) and runHistory turns it into a usageError (exit 2) — all valid records become unreadable from one bad line. This directly contradicts reader.go's own documented contract (lines 12-18) that a torn write or stray byte must never permanently brick 'atcr history'; malformed lines are skipped, but an over-long line is not. Empirically confirmed: a ledger of two valid records with one >1MiB junk line between them loads 0 records with an error.|In Load, detect errors.Is(sc.Err(), bufio.ErrTooLong) and skip past the oversized line instead of failing (e.g. fall back to a bufio.Reader with ReadString('\n') that tolerates long lines, advancing past the offending line). Add a test writing a >1MiB junk line between two valid records and assert both valid records still load.|error-handling|30|internal/history/reader.go:29-49|claude
MEDIUM|internal/history/capture.go:56|RecordReview dedupes findings by FindingID (file+line+problem, severity excluded by design) keeping the first occurrence, but pool findings.txt is a raw concatenation of every reviewer's rows — so the same finding can appear from two reviewers with different severities. The recorded Severity is then whichever reviewer's row happens to sort first in the pool file, an arbitrary order-dependent choice. Since the per-severity trend table is the feature's entire output, a finding can be attributed to a non-authoritative severity and the stored value is nondeterministic across pool orderings.|In the dedupe loop (capture.go:50-64), on a repeat id resolve severity deterministically by taking the max severity across duplicate rows (mirroring reconcile's max-severity rule) rather than first-wins. Add a test where two reviewers report the same id at LOW and HIGH and assert the stored record is HIGH regardless of row order.|correctness|30|internal/history/capture.go:43-64|claude
LOW|internal/history/writer.go:38|Append's doc comment claims the batch is written with a single O_APPEND write() call so concurrent 'atcr review' runs interleave only at batch boundaries, never mid-line. That guarantee is overstated: os.File.Write loops on short writes, so a large batch can be split across multiple write() syscalls, and under the documented concurrent-review use case another process's append can land between them, splitting one JSONL line and joining fragments of two records into one corrupt line (which the reader then silently skips, losing both records). Low probability in practice (records are small) but the doc asserts a guarantee the code does not provide.|Either bound the guarantee honestly in the comment (atomicity only holds when the kernel writes the batch in one syscall) or serialize appends with an advisory file lock (flock / O_EXCL lockfile) around the write. If keeping the current approach, correct the misleading comment.|error-handling|60|internal/history/writer.go:16-45|claude
LOW|internal/history/capture.go:38|RecordReview uses res.Findings from stream.ParseSource but silently discards res.Skipped (rows the parser rejected as malformed, e.g. an unescaped pipe producing a wrong column count — stream/parser.go:185). A finding a reviewer actually raised can therefore never enter the history ledger with zero signal that anything was lost, undercounting the trend table that is the feature's output.|In capture.go after ParseSource, when len(res.Skipped) > 0 log a warning with the skipped count (consistent with how the rest of the pipeline surfaces skipped rows) so silent undercount is observable. Add a test with one over-column pool row asserting a warning/skip count while valid rows still record.|error-handling|15|internal/history/capture.go:36-41|claude
LOW|internal/history/render.go:85|RenderTable writes package names and severity labels straight into markdown table cells with no escaping. Severity is reviewer/model-generated free text (a value like "HIGH / INJECTED" — using a pipe — normalizes into a spoofed extra column) and package names derive from finding file paths, which on POSIX may legally contain a pipe or newline. Either breaks the rendered table structure or injects fabricated rows/columns. No test covers a pipe or newline in a package or severity cell.|In render.go escape or reject pipe and control/newline characters in package and severity cells before writing (replace | with \\| and strip newlines), or validate severity/package against an allowed character class. Add a render test with a package and severity containing a pipe.|security|30|internal/history/render.go:63-102|claude

